    "ui_concept": {
      "type": "custom-liquid",
      "settings": {
        "section_visibility": "always",
        "custom_liquid": "<div class=\"ui-feature-shell\">\n  <section class=\"ui-section\">\n    <div class=\"ui-wrap\">\n      <div class=\"ui-section-head\">\n        <p class=\"ui-kicker\">The Concept</p>\n        <h2>What is a Universal In-Ear Monitor?</h2>\n        <p>A Universal In-Ear Monitor (UIEM) is a high-performance earphone designed to sit inside the ear canal using interchangeable silicone or foam ear tips. Unlike a custom IEM that is moulded from individual ear impressions, a universal uses a standardised shell shape engineered to fit the widest possible range of ear anatomies. The tips create the seal; the shell houses the drivers, crossover, and acoustic pathway.</p>\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"ui-article-body\">\n        <div class=\"ui-article-copy\">\n          <h3>A monitor, not an earbud</h3>\n          <p>The word \u201Cmonitor\u201D matters. A consumer earbud is tuned for casual enjoyment \u2014 often with a V-shaped curve that exaggerates bass and treble. A studio or stage monitor is tuned for accuracy: you hear what the microphone captured, what the mixer is sending, or what the mastering engineer intended. AAW universal monitors follow the same reference tuning targets as our custom line.</p>\n          <p>A universal IEM consists of a rigid shell \u2014 typically injection-moulded or 3D-printed resin \u2014 containing balanced armature drivers, dynamic drivers, or a hybrid of both. Sound travels from each driver through precision-bore tubing to a single nozzle. The user selects an ear tip that creates an acoustic seal in the ear canal. When the seal is correct, the monitor delivers its full frequency response, from sub-bass to upper treble, with consistent stereo imaging.</p>\n          <p>Universals are the most accessible entry point into reference-grade personal audio. They are used by musicians who need a backup to their customs, by audiophiles auditioning different sonic signatures, and by anyone who wants studio sound without the lead time of a custom build.</p>\n        </div>\n        <figure class=\"ui-article-figure\">\n          <img src=\"{{ 'a3h-lux-pair-wide.jpg' | asset_url }}\" alt=\"AAW universal in-ear monitor pair showing standardised shell design\" loading=\"lazy\">\n          <figcaption><b>AAW universal range</b><span>Standardised shells with interchangeable tips. Same drivers and tuning as their custom counterparts.</span></figcaption>\n        </figure>\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"ui-subhead\">A short history of the in-ear monitor</div>\n      <ul class=\"ui-timeline\" style=\"margin-top:0;\">\n        <li><b>1980s \u2014 The stage wedge problem</b>Floor monitors were loud, feedback-prone, and inconsistent night to night. Musicians needed a better way to hear themselves.</li>\n        <li><b>1995 \u2014 Jerry Harvey invents the custom IEM</b>Harvey built the first custom in-ear monitor for Alex Van Halen, combining hearing-aid shell technology with miniature balanced armature drivers. The CIEM was born.</li>\n        <li><b>2000s \u2014 Universal IEMs enter the market</b>Brands like Shure, Westone, and Ultimate Ears began offering universal-fit versions of their stage monitors. Audiophiles took notice. The category grew beyond the stage.</li>\n        <li><b>2014 \u2014 AAW is founded in Singapore</b>Advanced AcousticWerkes began building custom and universal IEMs from a single workshop. Hybrid driver configurations, tubeless designs, and proprietary tuning became the AAW signature.</li>\n        <li><b>Today \u2014 Universals rival customs in performance</b>With advanced tip materials like AAW\u2019s LiquidMorph, multi-driver hybrids, and switchable tuning, a well-designed universal can deliver 95% of the custom experience at a lower price and with zero wait time.</li>\n      </ul>\n    </div>\n  </section>\n</div>",
        "content_width": "large",
        "text_alignment": "left",
        "color_scheme": "primary",
        "top_space_desktop": 0,
        "bottom_space_desktop": 0,
